{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514008"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:17:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:17:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12262"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12262"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.18,0.47,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103566"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4784"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36805"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103566"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 40-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12 hour history of increasingly severe and unremitting upper abdominal pain. The pain is constant in nature and radiates through to his back. He has vomited twice since the pain started. The previous evening he had been binge-drinking with a group of friends. He does not take any medications and his medical history is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 94/62 mmHg, pulse 130/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 20/min, and Sa02 98% on room air. There is epigastric tenderness and the rest of the abdomen is soft. A serum lipase enzyme is 520 U/L (RR 0-160).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"From a diagnostic perspective, which one of the following imaging modalities is required at this stage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT abdomen","Abdominal ultrasound","No imaging required","Abdominal X-ray","MRCP"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has acute pancreatitis. Alcohol consumption (25-35%) is the second most common cause of acute pancreatitis, with most cases being gallstone-related (40-70%). The pain presents classically as a constant, severe epigastric pain that radiates to the back and improves on leaning forward. Other associated symptoms include nausea, vomiting, and fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBased on the revised Atlanta classification, a diagnosis of acute pancreatitis can be made when at least two of the following are present:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal pain suggestive of acute pancreatitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum amylase or lipase \u0026gt;3 times the upper normal value (RR 0\u2013160 U/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal imaging showing characteristics of acute pancreatitis (e.g. peripancreatic fluid buildup)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs since this patient has the classical symptoms of acute pancreatitis and a serum lipase \u0026gt;3 times the upper normal value, from a diagnostic perspective, he requires \u003Cstrong\u003Eno further imaging\u003C/strong\u003E. An\u003Cstrong\u003E abdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most useful initial imaging test to do to rule out the presence of gallstones - ie determining the underlying cause of the pancreatitis. A \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E would be helpful if the diagnosis was in doubt, as well as to monitor for acute complications of acute pancreatitis (e.g. pseudocyst, necrotising pancreatitis). An \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is of no diagnostic value, but could be used to visualise a functional ileus (due to pancreatic inflammation) should one be suspected. Lastly, \u003Cstrong\u003EMRCP\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in suspected biliary or pancreatic duct obstruction (e.g. gallstones, pancreatic or ampullary tumors).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnfortunately the reality of today\u2019s medical practice is that this patient is likely to go through the CT scanner in a desire to obtain a radiological diagnosis rather than rely on clinical acumen and some simple laboratory investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A diagnosis of acute pancreatitis can be made based on the Atlanta criteria."],"references":["Boxhoorn L, Voermans RP, Bouwense SA, et al. Acute pancreatitis. Lancet 2020; 396:726-34"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12262"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T20:09:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T20:10:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4784"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103566"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda